Hybrid Benchmarking of Quantum Breadth-First Search
Lara Lelakowski
Master´s thesis 2026

This repository contains the implementation and evaluation of a hybrid benchmarking approach for Quantum Breadth-First Search (QBFS).
The project was developed as part of a Master´s thesis. 

The goal of this work is to analyze the performance of the QBFS algorithm within Dinic´s algorithm. In this context,
the classical Breadth-First Search (BFS) is replaced by a quantum variant, the quantum Breadth-First Search (QBFS), 
enabling a comparison between the classical and quantum Dinic´s algorithm.

The project focuses on implementing the QBFS iteration count and the BFS within Dinic´s algorithm to be able to compare
the performance of the BFS and the number of gates used by the QBFS. The benchmarking approach is hybrid, combining classical
computation with a analytical quantum algorithm analysis.

Structure of the repository:
- 'BFS' implements the classical Breadth-First Search
- 'QSearchIterationCount' implements the iteration count to perform the QBFS
- 'DFS' implements the Depth-First Search used in Dinic´s algorithm
- 'Random Graph Generator' generates a pseudo-random graph for benchmarking
- 'BFS-QBFS without Dynic' shows the BFS and QBFS isolated on a random graph
- 'Dinic' is the final implementation, combining all components into a hybrid benchmarking implementation 
